\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:differentiable"

\end_inset

A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
differentiable at a point 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $c\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(a\right)}{x-a}
\]

\end_inset

exists as a real number.
 The function is said to be 
\emph on
differentiable 
\emph default
if it is differentiable at every point in the interior of its domain.
 If a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable everywhere, the derivative function is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}$
\end_inset

as in 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}\left(y\right)=\lim_{x\to y}\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}{x-y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The derivative is also denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{df}{dy}=f^{\prime}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 which captures the heuristic that the derivative can be thought as the
 ratio of small quantities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:derivativeConstant"

\end_inset

It should be immediately clearly that for any constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=a$
\end_inset

, its derivative is zero everywhere, and for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

, its derivative is 1 is everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:differentiableImpliesContinuous"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 be differentiable at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\left(a,b\right).$
\end_inset

Then it is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $c.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall that the limit of the product of two functions is the product of
 the limit, provided those individual limits exist.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\to c}f\left(x\right)-f\left(c\right) & =\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(c\right)}{x-c}x-c\\
 & =\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(c\right)}{x-c}\lim_{x\to c}x-c\\
 & =f^{\prime}\left(c\right)0\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The converse of this theorem is not true; for instance, consider that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert x\rvert$
\end_inset

 is continuous (this follows by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reverse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 triangle inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert\lvert x\rvert-\lvert y\rvert\rvert\leq\lvert x-y\rvert)$
\end_inset

.
 That it is not differentiable can be seen by looking at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to0^{-}}\frac{\lvert x\rvert}{x}=-1\neq1=\lim_{x\to0^{+}}\frac{\lvert x\rvert}{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:algebraOfDifferentiableFunctions"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g$
\end_inset

 be real-valued functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 that are differentiable at some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 .
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f+g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $fg$
\end_inset

 are differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}$
\end_inset

is also differentaible.
 The derivatives are given
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(f+g\right)^{\prime}\left(x\right) & =f^{\prime}\left(x\right)+g^{\prime}\left(x\right)\\
\left(fg\right)^{\prime}\left(x\right) & =f^{\prime}\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)+g^{\prime}\left(x\right)f\left(x\right)\\
\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)^{\prime} & \left(x\right)=\frac{f^{\prime}\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)-g^{\prime}\left(x\right)f\left(x\right)}{\left(g\left(x\right)\right)^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The first one, called the sum rule, follows by algebra of limits.
 The second, known as the product rule, follows by the same trick that is
 used to prove that the product of two sequences converges to the product
 of their limits.
 To reiterate, note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{f\left(y\right)g\left(y\right)-f\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)}{y-x} & =\frac{f\left(y\right)g\left(y\right)-f\left(y\right)g\left(x\right)+f\left(y\right)g\left(x\right)-f\left(x\right)g\left(x\right)}{x-c}\\
 & =\frac{f\left(y\right)\left(g\left(y\right)-g\left(x\right)\right)}{y-x}+\frac{g\left(x\right)\left(f\left(y\right)-f\left(x\right)\right)}{y-x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Taking limits and applying Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:differentiableImpliesContinuous"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gets the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Finally, the third result, called the quotient rule, follows as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\frac{f\left(y\right)}{g\left(y\right)}-\frac{f\left(x\right)}{g\left(x\right)}}{y-x} & =\frac{1}{g\left(x\right)g\left(y\right)}\left(\frac{f\left(y\right)g\left(x\right)-f\left(x\right)g\left(y\right)}{y-x}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{g\left(x\right)g\left(y\right)}\left(\frac{f\left(y\right)g\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)g\left(y\right)+f\left(y\right)g\left(y\right)-f\left(x\right)g\left(y\right)}{y-x}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{g\left(x\right)g\left(y\right)}\left(\frac{f\left(y\right)\left[g\left(x\right)-g\left(y\right)\right]}{y-x}+\frac{g\left(y\right)\left[f\left(y\right)-f\left(x\right)\right]}{y-x}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and taking limits and again applying the continuity of differentiable functions
 completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Power rule
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:powerRule"

\end_inset

The derivative of a real-valued function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 defined 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathds{Z}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\left(x\right)=nx^{n-1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First we examine the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 For the base cases of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 look at the remark above.
 Now suppose that the rule holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 Then, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n+1}=xx^{n},$
\end_inset

 we apply the product rule to yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx^{n+1}}{dx}=xnx^{n-1}+x^{n}=\left(n+1\right)x^{n}
\]

\end_inset

which completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To extend the result to negative integers, we can apply the quotient rule.
 Note that for a negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, we have some positive integern 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-n$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{m}=\frac{1}{x^{n}}$
\end_inset

 which has derivative (by applying the power rule for positive integers
 and the quoteint rule)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}\left(x\right)=\frac{-nx^{n-1}}{x^{2n}}=mx^{m-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The power rule also holds for rational exponents; we shall establish this
 fact after we state the chain rule.
 For real exponents, the power rule holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq0$
\end_inset

 since we define 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}:=\exp\left(a\log\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\R$
\end_inset

.
 Since the logarithm is only defined on the positive reals, the result only
 extends to that case (the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is trivial).
 We shall prove this after we construct the exponential and natural logarithm
 functions in Appendix section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:specialFunctions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:differentiabilityOfPolynomials"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in P_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

degree polynomials.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable and its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\in P_{n-1}\left(x\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}x^{i}.$
\end_inset

 By the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sum rule
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

product rule
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

power rule
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}\left(x\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}ix^{i-1}\in P_{n-1}\left(x\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
An immediate corrolary is that every polynomial is infinitely differentiable.
 Infinitely differentiable functions are called 
\emph on
smooth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chain rule
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:chainRuleR"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:C\subseteq\R\to\R$
\end_inset

 be differentiable at some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in D$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:D\subseteq\R\to\R$
\end_inset

 be differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(c\right)\in D.$
\end_inset

 Then the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 with derivative 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f\circ g\right)^{\prime}\left(c\right)=f^{\prime}\left(g\left(c\right)\right)g^{\prime}\left(c\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We omit the proof of this theorem right now; we will prove it in the more
 general setting of derivatves on functions between Banach spaces in the
 next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:rationalPowerRule"

\end_inset

A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{r}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\R$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\left(x\right)=rx^{r-1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will establish the result when 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

 (when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, the derivative is 0 as established in an earlier remark).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\mathds{Z}$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right):=x^{q}$
\end_inset

 has derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\prime}\left(x\right)=qx^{q-1}$
\end_inset

 by the integral power rule
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:powerRule"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Then, observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(f\left(x\right)\right)=x^{p}$
\end_inset

 and so applying the chain rule on the left hand hand side and the integral
 power rule on the right hand side, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
qf\left(x\right)^{q-1}f^{\prime}\left(x\right) & =px^{p-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be re-arranged to yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f^{\prime}\left(x\right) & =\frac{px^{p-1}}{qf\left(x\right)^{q-1}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{p}{q}\right)x^{p-1-\frac{p}{q}\left(q-1\right)}\\
 & =\frac{p}{q}x^{\frac{p}{q}-1}\\
 & =rx^{r-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which completes the proof.
\end_layout

