\begin_layout Standard
Recall that in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:densities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we showed that for a measure space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 and a non-negative measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\nonnegMeasurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 , the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\left(A\right):=\lebInt{\mu}{f\indicate_{A}}$
\end_inset

is a measure.
 Moreover, in the remark following the proposition, we observed that such
 a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 was 
\emph on
absolutely continuous 
\emph default
with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, that is to say, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F,\mu(A)=0\implies\nu(A)=0.$
\end_inset

 Further, we also claimed that every absolutely continuous measure could
 be represented this way i.e as an integral with respect to the dominating
 measure.
 In other words, we claimed that there was always an 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\nonnegMeasurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 such that this relation would hold.
 It turns out we can establish a slightly stronger result, which in turn
 is key to establishing the fundamental theorem of calculus for the Lebesgue
 measure.
 What we can show, using the Hilbert space machinery we developed earlier,
 is that we can decompose a measure (relative to another measure) into two
 measures that are in some sense orthogonal.
 This is in direct correspondence with the decomposition of Hilbert spaces
 given to us by the projection theorem (Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:projectionThm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To motivate how the Hilbert space theory can be useful in this context,
 we can begin with a change of perspective in the spirit of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:integralMeasureEquivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that saying 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(A)=\lebInt{\mu}{f\indicate_{A}}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $\lebInt{\nu}g=\lebInt{\mu}{fg}\forall g\in\Lp1{\X,\F,\nu}.$
\end_inset

 The right hand side is the inner product associated with the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp2{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and so we wish to show that a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to\lebInt{\nu}g$
\end_inset

 can be represented as an inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp2{\mu}.$
\end_inset

 At this juncture, one can guess that the Riesz representation theorem for
 Hilbert spaces is clearly right tool to finish off the proof; however,
 several hurdles remain.
 For one, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to\lebInt{\nu}g$
\end_inset

 a linear functional on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp1{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and it is not 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp2{\mu}.$
\end_inset

 Further, it is unclear whether our functional is bounded, which is a necessary
 condition for the theorem to apply.
 The following lemma provides the conditions under which the theorem finds
 purchase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lemma:LebesgueRadonNikodym"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu$
\end_inset

 are two 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

finite measures on 
\begin_inset Formula $\F$
\end_inset

, then there exists some non-negative (almost everywhere with respect to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

) measurable function 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\nonnegMeasurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 and a set 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(G)=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(A\right)=\lebInt{\mu}{k\indicate_{A}}+\nu(A\cap G)
\]

\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu-$
\end_inset

almost-everywhere and the set 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

